# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1832-democratic-national-convention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The **1821 United States Senate election in New York** was held on February 6, 1821, by the New York State Legislature to elect a U.S. senator (Class 1) to represent the State of New York in the United States Senate.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Nathan Sanford had been elected in 1815 to this seat, and his term would expire on March 3, 1821.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Although nominally in the same party, the Democratic-Republicans were split into two fiercely opposing factions: the "Clintonians" (allies of Governor DeWitt Clinton), and "Bucktails" (a combine of the Tammany members from New York City and Clinton's upstate adversaries led by Martin Van Buren).
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The Federalist Party had disbanded, the larger part joining the Clintonians, the others the Bucktails.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] At the State election in April 1820, although Clinton was re-elected Governor, a Bucktails majority was elected to the assembly, and five of the eight state senators up for renewal were Bucktails.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The 44th New York State Legislature met from November 7 to 20, 1820; and from January 9 to April 3, 1821, at Albany, New York.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The party strength in the assembly as shown by the vote for Speaker was: 69 for Bucktail Peter Sharpe and 52 for Clintonian John C.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Before the election, a caucus of Democratic-Republican State legislators was held with 82 members present.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] 58 voted for Van Buren, 24 for Sanford, and Martin Van Buren was declared nominated.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In the election, he received the votes of the Bucktails.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Disregarding the caucus nominee, a practice now already established, the incumbent U.S.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Senator Nathan Sanford received the votes of the Clintonians.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Martin Van Buren was the choice of both the Assembly and the Senate, and was declared elected.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 26 to December 2, 1824.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Andrew Jackson, John Quincy Adams, Henry Clay and William Crawford were the primary contenders for the presidency.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The result of the election was inconclusive, as no candidate won a majority of the electoral vote.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In the election for vice president, John C.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun was elected with a comfortable majority of the vote.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Because none of the candidates for president garnered an electoral vote majority, the U.S.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] House of Representatives, under the provisions of the Twelfth Amendment, held a contingent election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] On February 9, 1825, the House voted (with each state delegation casting one vote) to elect John Quincy Adams as president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party had won six consecutive presidential elections and by 1824 was the only national political party.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] However, as the election approached, the presence of multiple viable candidates resulted in there being multiple nominations by the contending factions, signaling the splintering of the party and an end to the Era of Good Feelings, as well as the First Party System.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won New England, Jackson and Adams split the mid-Atlantic states, Jackson and Clay split the Western states, and Jackson and Crawford split the Southern states.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson finished with a plurality of the popular vote (there was no popular vote in six states including New York, the most populous state), and also of the electoral vote (due to the Three-fifths Compromise), while the other three candidates each finished with a significant share of the votes.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Clay, who had finished fourth, was eliminated.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was the first son of a former president to become president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] This is one of two presidential elections (along with the 1800 election) that have been decided in the House.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] It is also one of five elections in which the winner did not achieve at least a plurality of the national popular vote and the only election in which the candidate who received the most electoral votes from the Electoral College did not win the election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] It is also, to date, the election with the lowest popular vote percentage for an elected president (32.7%).
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The Era of Good Feelings, associated with the administration of President James Monroe, was a time of reduced emphasis on political party identity.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] With the Federalists discredited, Democratic-Republicans adopted some key Federalist economic programs and institutions.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] An unintended consequence of wide single-party identification was reduced party discipline.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Rather than political harmony, factions arose within the party.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe attempted to improve discipline by appointing leading statesmen to his Cabinet, including Secretary of State John Quincy Adams of Massachusetts, Secretary of the Treasury William H.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford of Georgia, and Secretary of War John C.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] General Andrew Jackson of Tennessee led high-profile military missions.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Only House Speaker Henry Clay of Kentucky held political power independent of Monroe.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] He refused to join the cabinet and remained critical of the administration.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Two key events, the Panic of 1819 and the Missouri crisis of 1820, influenced and reshaped politics.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The economic downturn broadly harmed workers, the sectional disputes over slavery expansion raised tensions, and both events plus other factors drove demand for increased democratic control.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Social disaffection would help motivate revival of rivalrous political parties in the near future, though these had not yet formed by the time of the 1824 election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The previous competition between the Federalist Party and the Democratic-Republican Party collapsed after the War of 1812 due to the disintegration of the Federalists' popular appeal.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] President James Monroe of the Democratic-Republicans was able to run effectively unopposed in the 1820 election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Like previous presidents who had been elected to two terms, Monroe declined to seek re-nomination for a third term.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The presidential nomination was thus left wide open within the Democratic-Republican Party, the only remaining major national political entity.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] During the first year of Monroe's second term, it was said that 17 names had been mentioned as possible candidates, although formal nominations did not occur until late December.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Among these possible candidates, William H.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford was seen as the most formidable, with many observers anticipating that John Quincy Adams would be his primary rival, and Henry Clay regarded as a likely outside contender.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford, a native of the Georgia frontier, was physically imposing and a powerful political figure.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] He was the first president pro tem of the Senate to be elected continuingly and had nearly beaten Monroe for the party nomination in 1816.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] As Secretary of the Treasury, he had helped to reorganized the nation's finances after the War of 1812 and establish the Second Bank of the United States.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] As such, he came to be seen as the treasury candidate.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford cultivated a strong base of support for the nomination, especially among influential political figures who could manage the congressional caucus and had, in the words of William Lowndes, his own "Organized Party" (the Old Republicans).
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Opponents accused him of consolidating power through the Tenure of Office Act of 1820, which required financial officeholders to be reappointed every four years.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In creating a web of support among self-interested agents, Crawford became a man suspected of deliberately contriving his own election, something feared by all others.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Despite these accusations, his supporters believed that he was not the conniving, maneuvering self-seeker his rivals branded him to be.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] It is impossible to know for certain, however, as little of his personal correspondence survives.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The first people to be publicly nominated as candidates were Calhoun and Lowndes.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun had been clashing with Crawford since the spring of 1820, when the latter began a retrenchment campaign in response to the Panic of 1819.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun and his partisans viewed the effort as designed to emasculate the Department of War and discredit its secretary, especially as Congress failed to pass similar proposed reductions in the civil list.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun, up until this point a staunch nationalist, shared many policy positions with Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Though claiming to prefer Adams, he feared that Adams could not defeat Crawford in the Southern and Middle states.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Therefore, it fell upon him to challenge the assumption that Crawford was the favorite of the Southeast, hopefully defeating Crawford and his radicals.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Overestimating his popularity, Calhoun believed that he could build a solid core of support by appealing to the economic interests of the two most powerful states, New York and Pennsylvania, and by consolidating his home base in the Southeast.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In particular, he focused on Pennsylvania, where he made relations with the Family Party—a group of young Republican politicians in Philadelphia, led by George M.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Ingham, who opposed the state's Republican leaders that favored Crawford.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Before the nomination, he had informed Lowndes of his intention to run for president early in his stay at Calhoun's residence in Washington, which began in December 1821.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Lowndes, while having spoken positively of the other men, assured Calhoun he preferred his election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] However, during Lowndes' journey to Washington, and without his knowledge, lowcountry moderates in the South Carolina legislature made an unprecedented move by attempting to nominate Lowndes.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] This effort was led by James Hamilton Jr., the Charleston delegation, and others from the tidewater parishes and Middle District counties east of the Broad River.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] They called a caucus of the legislature, which met in the hall of representatives on December 18, with about 2/3 of both houses in attendance.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Opposition to the motion consisted primarily of upcountry partisans of Calhoun who, caught off guard, argued for delay, declaring the proposal premature and condemning the very idea that a single small state should attempt to name a president for the whole nation.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] While recognizing Calhoun's credentials, Lowndes' supporters argued that he was a more nationally prominent figure who would be more acceptable to citizens across the country.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The motion to recommend Lowndes for president narrowly passed, 58 to 54, embarrassing Calhoun's campaign.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The two men agreed not to alter their plans.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun would enter the race as planned, while Lowndes would neither decline the nomination nor encourage an active campaign on his behalf, but follow the course dictated by his health.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] As this would most likely result in a voyage abroad, effectively removing Lowndes from further consideration, the difficulty presented by his nomination would be resolved, and supporters could transfer their backing to Calhoun.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Despite this, his supporters remained insistent on his candidacy and encouraged him to stay.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Lowndes died on October 27, 1822, en route to a recuperative visit to England.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The next month the legislature transferred their nomination to Calhoun.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Later, in February 1824, Dallas gave his support to Jackson's presidential campaign, with Calhoun as his running mate.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] While Republicans in Northern states wished to support a man of their own, many were reluctant to rally behind Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] By early 1823, critics among his supporters complained that Adams was "too fastidious and reserved," failing to engage in the political collaboration expected of a leader.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] They argued that presidents were no longer chosen purely on merit but rather through the influence of politicians and newspapers.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Rather than endure such a leader, many potential supporters began searching for an alternative Northern candidate, though this effort ultimately proved fruitless.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Rufus King was too old and also unwilling.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Tompkins had long-since been dismissed as a viable successor to Monroe due to a combination of health problems and a financial dispute with the federal government, and he formally ruled himself out of making a presidential run at the start of 1824.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Secretary of the Navy Smith Thompson, believing his New York ties might make him a viable option, delayed accepting a seat on the U.S.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Supreme Court for eight months before being persuaded that he stood no chance of the presidency.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, while having been supported by a small minority for president in 1820, suffered from the memory of his past involvements with Federalists, and in 1822 had become too electorally weak to compete, let alone win New York presidentially against the state's political machine.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The *Niles' Weekly Register*, reporting on Washington politics in its January 26, 1822, issue, reported the names of Calhoun, Thompson, Clinton, Lowndes, Tompkins, Adams, Clay, and Crawford as being put forth as candidates.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The newspaper also reported that "one or two others are casually spoken of" but did not identify them.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Lowndes' nomination had sparked intense speculation in Washington during the first week of the new year, concerned with the ramifications of the way Lowndes had been nominated.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In a letter to his wife, Lowndes stated, "The House is in terrible confusion.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] I thought when I came here that the question was in fact confined to two persons Mr Crawford and Mr Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] That year, Kentucky and Missouri legislature caucuses nominated Clay, and Tennessee nominated Jackson.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In January 1823, a meeting of Ohio legislators approved resolutions naming Clay.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In early 1823, the legislatures of Massachusetts and Maine stated a preference for Adams but did not make a formal nomination, as they wished to ensure party unity nationwide.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In January 1824, a caucus in the Mississippi legislature divided evenly between supporting Adams and Jackson.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In Rhode Island, the "State Junta" initially committed itself in early 1824 to supporting the caucus candidate but soon realized they could not sway public opinion against Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Consequently, they refrained from pressing for Crawford out of fear of jeopardizing their state ticket.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In early 1824, the Connecticut legislature nominated Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In March 1824, a state party convention at Harrisburg nominated Jackson.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In June 1824, the New Hampshire legislature nominated Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The legislatures of Maine, New York, Virginia, and Georgia were in favor of the Congressional nominating caucus.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] While not always popular, in past elections the party had relied on a congressional caucus, sometimes referred to as the "King Caucus," to nominate their presidential candidates, a process that had consistently succeeded in identifying the party favorite.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Now, however, there was no certainty that the caucus would work again.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Proponents, many of whom supported William H.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford, argued that it was essential for maintaining the stability of the republic and ensuring party unity on the presidential question.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Opponents, including some of Crawford's own supporters, criticized the process as limiting the people's choice and effectively predetermining the outcome of the popular election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The strongest opposition came from Jacksonians.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] They viewed it as emblematic of the insider manipulation they sought to dismantle.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] On the other hand, New England Republicans, drawn to traditional party practices, had no such objection, and about 20 were believed to be willing to support Crawford if they could not have Adams, until Adams declared he would not accept a nomination for any office from a congressional caucus.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In most delegations there were one or two representatives who, if left to themselves, were willing to attend the caucus.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford hoped to secure more than the 65 ballots that Monroe had obtained in 1816.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In early February 1824, a majority of congressmen signed a public statement that they would not attend a nominating caucus.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] They believed that by refusing to attend instead of killing it, the caucus system would collapse on its own.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Gallatin had not sought the vice presidential nomination and soon withdrew at Crawford's request.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Gallatin was also dissatisfied with repeated attacks on his credibility made by the other candidates.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] He was replaced by North Carolina senator Nathaniel Macon.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams sought to have Jackson be his vice-presidential running mate and Louisa Adams hosted a ball in honor of the Battle of New Orleans' ninth anniversary.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] He had supported Jackson during his invasion of Florida while Clay and Crawford opposed him, causing Jackson to oppose them.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Clay supporters in the Tennessee legislature nominated Jackson for president in 1822, as an attempt to weaken Crawford in the state.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Martin Van Buren and his political machine supported Crawford in New York.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] During the selection of New York's electors Van Buren was able to deny Clay enough support to prevent him from being eligible for the contingent election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] All four candidates were nominated by at least one state legislature.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Andrew Jackson was recruited to run for the office of the president by the state legislature of Tennessee.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson did not seek the task of running for president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, he wished to retire to his estate on the outskirts of Nashville, called the Hermitage.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Candidates drew voter support by different states and sections.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams dominated the popular vote in New England and won some support elsewhere, Clay dominated his home state of Kentucky and won pluralities in two neighboring states, and Crawford won the Virginia vote overwhelmingly and polled well in North Carolina.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had geographically the broadest support, though there were heavy vote concentrations in his home state of Tennessee and in Pennsylvania and populous areas where even he ran poorly.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Policy played a reduced role in the election, though positions on tariffs and internal improvements did create significant disagreements.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Both Adams and Jackson supporters backed Secretary of War John C.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun of South Carolina for vice president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] He easily secured the majority of electoral votes for that office.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The campaigning for presidential election of 1824 took many forms.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Contrafacta, or well known songs and tunes whose lyrics have been altered, were used to promote political agendas and presidential candidates.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Below can be found a sound clip featuring "Hunters of Kentucky", a tune written by Samuel Woodsworth in 1815 under the title "The Unfortunate Miss Bailey".
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Contrafacta such as this one, which promoted Andrew Jackson as a national hero, have been a long-standing tradition in presidential elections.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Another form of campaigning during this election was through newsprint.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Political cartoons and partisan writings were best circulated among the voting public through newspapers.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun was one of the candidates most directly involved through his participation in the publishing of the newspaper *The Patriot* as a member of the editorial staff.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] This was a sure way to promote his own political agendas and campaign.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In contrast, most candidates involved in early 19th century elections did not run their own political campaigns.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Instead it was left to volunteer citizens and partisans to speak on their behalf.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The 1824 presidential election marked the final collapse of the Republican-Federalist political framework.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The electoral map confirmed the candidates' sectional support, with Adams winning in New England, Jackson having wide voter appeal, Clay attracting votes from the West, and Crawford attracting votes from the eastern South.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson earned only a plurality of electoral votes.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the presidential election was decided by the House of Representatives, which elected John Quincy Adams on the first ballot.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun, supported by Adams and Jackson, easily won the vice presidency, not requiring a contingent election in the Senate.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's electoral college plurality was the result of the Three-fifths Compromise.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The electoral college results would have been 83 for Adams and 77 for Jackson without the inflated electoral count of slaveholding states.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern-day presidential elections.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who a particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given candidate.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Jackson electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Jackson would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] As no presidential candidate had won an absolute electoral vote majority, the responsibility for electing a new president devolved upon the U.S.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] House of Representatives, which held a contingent election on February 9, 1825.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] As prescribed by the Twelfth Amendment, the House was limited to choosing from among the three candidates who received the most electoral votes: Andrew Jackson, John Quincy Adams, and William Crawford; Henry Clay, who had finished fourth, was eliminated.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Each state delegation, voting *en bloc*, had a single vote.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] There were 24 states at the time, thus an absolute majority of 13 votes was required for victory.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Even if Clay had wished to align with Crawford over Jackson, which was highly unlikely in any event since Clay's policy differences with Crawford were even deeper, especially on matters of the tariff, Crawford had been in poor health, and no path to victory was evident.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Daniel Pope Cook, Illinois' sole representative, was anti-slavery and gave his support to Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] James Buchanan attempted to make a compromise with Clay in which Jackson would make him Secretary of State in exchange for his support.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Clay instead gave his support to Adams and was able to have the Kentucky, Missouri, and Ohio delegations support him.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Illinois, Louisiana, and Maryland, which Jackson won during the election, had their delegations support Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren attempted to have New York's delegation be divided between Adams and Crawford in order to increase its power and make a deal with one of them.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] However, Stephen Van Rensselaer, a Federalist allied with Van Buren, voted for Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren stated that Van Rensselaer found a ballot for Adams on the floor while Van Rensselaer, in his letter to Governor DeWitt Clinton, stated that he voted for Adams as he was bound to win and that he wanted to shorten "the long agony".
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren supported Jackson during the 1828 election and aided in Calhoun's selection as vice president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Ignoring the nonbinding directive of the Kentucky legislature that its House delegation choose Jackson, the delegation voted 8–4 for Adams instead.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, Adams was elected president on the first ballot, with 13 states, followed by Jackson with seven, and Crawford with four.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' victory shocked Jackson, who, as the winner of a plurality of both the popular and electoral votes, expected the House to choose him.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Not long before the contingent House election, an anonymous statement appeared in a Philadelphia paper, called the *Columbian Observer*.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The statement, said to be from a member of Congress, essentially accused Clay of selling Adams his support for the office of Secretary of State.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] No formal investigation was conducted, so the matter was neither confirmed nor denied.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] When Clay was indeed offered the position after Adams was victorious, he opted to accept and continue to support the administration he voted for, knowing that declining the position would not have helped to dispel the rumors brought against him.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson referred to Clay as the "Judas of the West".
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] By appointing Clay his Secretary of State, President Adams essentially declared him heir to the presidency, as Adams and his three predecessors had all served as Secretary of State.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson and his followers accused Adams and Clay of striking a "corrupt bargain", and the Jacksonians would campaign on this claim for the next four years, ultimately helping Jackson defeat Adams in 1828.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Ironically, Adams offered Jackson a position in his Cabinet as Secretary of War, which Jackson declined to accept.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] House of Representatives after the 1824–25 elections and obtained the speakership for John W.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' relationship with Calhoun deteriorated, with Calhoun opposing Clay's appointment as Secretary of State due to his own presidential ambitions.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In June 1826, Calhoun gave his support to Jackson for the 1828 election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 New York gubernatorial election** was held from November 3 to 5, 1828.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Governor DeWitt Clinton died in office on February 11, 1828.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Lieutenant Governor Nathaniel Pitcher succeeded him but was not a candidate for election to the next term.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] United States Senator Martin Van Buren was elected Governor over United States Supreme Court Justice Smith Thompson and journalist Solomon Southwick.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] This is the first election to feature a winning candidate who eventually became President of the United States.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] This is the first election to also feature a winning candidate who eventually became both Vice President of the United States and President of the United States.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The Democratic Party nominated U.S. senator Martin Van Buren.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] They nominated former U.S. representative and Judge of the Seventh Circuit Enos T.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The National Republican Party nominated Supreme Court Justice Smith Thompson.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] They nominated state assemblyman Francis Granger for Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The Anti-Masonic Party nominated newspaper publisher Solomon Southwick.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] They nominated state senator John Crary for Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Van Buren was sworn into office as governor on January 1, 1829, but quickly resigned from office on March 12, 1829, to serve as United States Secretary of State and was succeeded by Lieutenant Governor Enos T.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 2, 1828.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Just as in the 1824 election, President John Quincy Adams of the National Republican Party faced Andrew Jackson of the Democratic Party, making the election the second rematch in presidential history.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties were new organizations, and this was the first presidential election their nominees contested.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] With the collapse of the Federalist Party, four members of the Democratic-Republican Party, including Jackson and Adams, had sought the presidency in the 1824 election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had won a plurality (but not majority) of both the electoral vote and popular vote in the 1824 election, but had lost the contingent election that was held in the House of Representatives.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the aftermath of the election, Jackson's supporters accused Adams and Henry Clay of having reached a "corrupt bargain" in which Clay helped Adams win the contingent election in return for the position of Secretary of State.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] After the 1824 election, Jackson's supporters immediately began plans for a campaign in 1828, and the Democratic-Republican Party fractured into the National Republican Party and the Democratic Party during Adams's presidency.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The 1828 campaign was marked by large amounts of "mudslinging", as both parties attacked the personal qualities of the opposing party's candidate.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson dominated in the South and the West, aided in part by the passage of the Tariff of 1828.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] With the ongoing expansion of the right to vote to most white men, the election marked a dramatic expansion of the electorate, with 9.5% of Americans casting a vote for president, compared with 3.4% in 1824.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Several states transitioned to a popular vote for president, leaving South Carolina and Delaware as the only states in which the legislature chose presidential electors.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson decisively won the election, carrying 55.5% of the popular vote and 178 electoral votes, to Adams' 83.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The election marked the rise of Jacksonian Democracy and the transition from the First Party System to the Second Party System.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Historians debate the significance of the election, with many arguing that it marked the beginning of modern American politics by removing key barriers to voter participation and establishing a stable two-party system.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson became the first president whose home state was neither Massachusetts nor Virginia, while Adams was the second to lose re-election, following his father John Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay, unsuccessful candidate and Speaker of the House at the time, despised Jackson, in part due to their fight for Western votes during the election, and he chose to support Adams, which led to Adams being elected president on the first ballot.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] A few days after the election, Adams appointed Clay his Secretary of State, a position held by Adams and his three immediate predecessors prior to becoming president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson and his followers promptly accused Clay and Adams of striking a "corrupt bargain," and continued to lambaste the president until the 1828 election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In 1824, the national Democratic-Republican Party collapsed as national politics became increasingly polarized between supporters of Adams and supporters of Jackson.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In a prelude to the presidential election, the Jacksonians bolstered their numbers in Congress in the 1826 congressional elections, with Jackson ally Andrew Stevenson chosen as the new Speaker of the House of Representatives in 1827 over Adams ally Speaker, John W.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In October 1825, the Tennessee legislature re-nominated Jackson for president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional opponents of Adams, including former William H.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford supporter Martin Van Buren, rallied around Jackson's candidacy.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's supporters called themselves *Democrats*, and would formally organize as the Democratic Party shortly after his election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In hopes of uniting those opposed to Adams, Jackson ran on a ticket with Calhoun.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] No congressional nominating caucus or national convention was held.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' relationship with Vice President John C.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun deteriorated, with Calhoun opposing Clay's appointment as Secretary of State due to his own presidential ambitions.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun's stance on the removal of Native Americans was not accepted by the Georgian electors who instead voted for William Smith.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren, who supported Crawford during the 1824 election, supported Jackson during the 1828 election and aided in the selection of Calhoun as vice president in order to prevent DeWitt Clinton, his political enemy, from being selected.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren arranged for incidents to divide Calhoun and Adams such as him abstaining from a vote on tariff legislation supported by Adams in order for Calhoun to break the tie by voting against it.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Ritchie, editor of the *Richmond Examiner*, was one of the leading supporters of Crawford during the 1824 election and Van Buren convinced him to support Jackson.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren convinced him of an alliance "between the planters of the South and the plain Republicans of the North".
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was re-nominated on the endorsement of state legislatures and partisan rallies.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] As with the Democrats, no nominating caucus or national convention was held.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams chose Secretary of the Treasury Richard Rush, a Pennsylvanian known for his protectionist views, as his running mate.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, who was personally popular in New England, hoped to assemble a coalition in which Clay attracted Western voters, Rush attracted voters in the middle states, and Webster won over former members of the Federalist Party.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams support in New York aligned with the Anti-Masonic Party and Thurlow Weed, his campaign manager in the state, was sympathetic to the anti-masonic movement.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was marked by large amounts of nasty "mudslinging." Jackson's marriage, for example, came in for the vicious attack.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Charles Hammond, in his *Cincinnati Gazette*, asked: "Ought a convicted adulteress and her paramour husband be placed in the highest offices of this free and Christian land?" At the time of the election, Mr. and Mrs.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had been happily, legally married for almost 35 years, but when they met, Rachel had been legally married to Lewis Robards.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the Adams campaign managers' hands, this became a scandal.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Decades later, their youthful love story became a political liability.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson believed that attacks on him were personal vendettas consequent to past disputes, writing, "I am branded with every crime, and Doctor McNary, Col.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Erwin, Anderson and Williams are associated for this purpose." One thing that all these men had in common is that they had all known and/or been business partners and/or been military comrades of Jackson going back decades.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's campaigners fired back by claiming that while serving as minister to Russia, Adams had procured a young girl to serve as a prostitute for Emperor Alexander I.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] They also stated that Adams had a billiard table in the White House and that he had charged the government for it.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] (In fact Adams while minister to Russia had employed a young girl as a maid to his wife; the girl had written a letter which had been intercepted by the Russian postal services.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander I had been curious to meet the letter writer publicly at court and Adams had done so.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The billiard table was Adams' personal property; a bill for repairing it had been accidentally included in the White House expense accounts.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams also came under attack for having a chess set).
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson also came under heavy attack as a slave trader who bought and sold slaves and moved them about in defiance of modern standards of morality (he was not attacked for merely owning slaves used in plantation work).
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Coffin Handbills attacked Jackson for his courts-martial, execution of deserters, and massacres of Indian villages, and also his habit of dueling and that he supposedly fought over 100 duels.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, Jackson had only fought three duels: in the first both men had fired at each other but made up; in the second duel, Jackson vs John Sevier, it had taken place but only two persons not connected with either party had been slightly injured.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The third duel was with Charles Dickinson in which Dickinson was mortally wounded while Jackson was left with a bullet in his chest.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] A so-called fourth duel between Jackson and Thomas Hart Benton was in fact a frontier brawl which left Jackson badly wounded in the shoulder.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] That said the list of violent incidents involving Andrew Jackson began with his arrival in Tennessee in the 1780s and continued apace for years.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Ezra Stiles Ely attacked Adams' Unitarian beliefs and called for Christians to vote for Jackson.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson avoided articulating issue positions, instead campaigning on his personal qualities and his opposition to Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams avoided popular campaigning, instead emphasizing his support of specific issues.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's praise of internal improvements in Europe, such as "lighthouses of the skies" (observatories), in his first annual message to Congress, and his suggestion that Congress not be "palsied by the will of our constituents" were given attention in and out of the press.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] People kissed babies, had picnics, and started many other traditions during the campaign.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson wrote of the outcome of the contingent election of 1825 in a letter to William H.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the next election, Jackson's and Adams's supporters saw value in establishing the opinion of Jefferson in regards to their respective candidates and against their opposition.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson died on July 4, 1826, on the same day as his predecessor, John Adams, Adams's father.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Webster recorded that Jefferson told him in December 1824 that Jackson was a dangerous man unfit for the presidency.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Historian Sean Wilentz described Webster's account of the meeting as "not wholly reliable." Biographer Robert V.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Gilmer accused Coles of misrepresentation, in Jefferson's opinion had changed, Gilmer said.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's son-in-law, former Virginia Governor Thomas Mann Randolph Jr., said in 1826 that Jefferson had a "strong repugnance" to Henry Clay.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Others said the same thing, but Coles could not believe Jefferson's opinion had changed.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Giles released a letter from Jefferson meant to be kept private to Thomas Ritchie's *Richmond Enquirer*.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It was written after Adams's first annual message to Congress and it contained an attack from Jefferson on the incumbent administration.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Giles omitted a prior letter of Jefferson's praise of Adams for his role in the embargo of 1808.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson Randolph soon collected and published Jefferson's correspondence.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] 22.2% of the voting age population and 57.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] All of the states, except for Delaware and South Carolina, selected their electors through a popular vote.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The selection of electors began on October 31 with elections in Ohio and Pennsylvania and ended on November 13 with elections in North Carolina.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Electoral College met on December 3.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won the same states that his father had won in the election of 1800 (the New England states, New Jersey, and Delaware) and Maryland, but Jackson won all other states and won the election in a landslide.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party in Georgia was hopelessly divided into two factions (Troup and Clark) at the time.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Despite this, both factions nominated Jackson for President, with the election being primarily a test of the strength of these two factions - the Adams electors ran a very poor third, with just 3.21% of the vote.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The winning slate, which received a 3,000 vote majority.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson received 50.3% of the vote in states without slavery while he received 72.6% of the vote in states with slavery.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] He received 200,000 votes in the South and 400,000 votes in the North, but the Three-fifths Compromise, which inflated the South's electoral votes, resulted in him receiving 105 electoral votes from the South and 73 votes from the North.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election in American history in which the incumbent president lost re-election despite winning a greater share of the popular vote than in the previous election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' loss was also the second time an elected president lost the popular vote twice, this also occurred with Benjamin Harrison in 1888 and 1892, and Donald Trump who lost the popular vote in 2016 and 2020.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which the Democrats won Kentucky until 1856.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It is also the only election where Maine, New Hampshire, New Jersey, and Vermont voted for the National Republicans, and the last time that New Hampshire voted against the Democrats until 1856.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only election in which an electoral vote split occurred in Maine until the election of 2016, the first election in which the winning ticket did not have a north–south balance, and the first election in which two northerners ran against two southerners.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] (b) *Votes cast for Jackson electors nominated by the Clark faction of the Democratic Party of Georgia.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Two tickets pledged to Jackson ran in this state; the Clark ticket was defeated by electors nominated by the Troup faction.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] There were two Jackson tickets in Georgia representing different factions of the party.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Troup faction "won" with 9,712 votes and the Clarke faction lost with 7,991.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] They are combined here, though legally this is incorrect.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The state rejected returns from 10 counties and 8 others submitted none.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Including the rejected returns, the total votes are Jackson (Troup) 10,508, Jackson (Clarke) 8,854 and Adams, 642.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In Maryland's 3rd and 4th districts, voters voted for two electors, with each pledged to one candidate or another.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The votes in the 3rd were 6,177 for William Fitzhugh Jr. and 6,164 for William Tyler, both for Jackson, versus 6,117 for George Baltzell and William Price for Adams.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the 4th the votes were 6,058 for Benjamin Chew Howard and James Sewell for Jackson versus 5,743 and 5,742 for the Adams electors.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Note: Dubin mistakenly swapped the 3rd and 4th districts in his book, but that has been corrected here.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Two statewide electors were chosen by the electors elected at the district level.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Rachel Jackson had been having chest pains throughout the campaign, and she was traumatized by the personal attacks on her marriage.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] She became ill and died on December 22, 1828.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson accused the Adams campaign, and Henry Clay even more so, of causing her death, saying, "I can and do forgive all my enemies.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Andrew Jackson was sworn in as president on March 4, 1829.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] After the inauguration, a mob entered the White House to shake the new president's hand, damaging the furniture and lights.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson escaped through the back, and large punch bowls were set up to lure the crowd outside.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Conservatives were horrified at this event, and held it up as a portent of terrible things to come from the first Democratic president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] When Jackson arrived in Washington, D.C., he was to pay the customary courtesy call on the outgoing president, but he refused to do so.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] John Quincy Adams responded by refusing to go to the inauguration of Andrew Jackson, similar to his father who did not attend the inauguration of Thomas Jefferson 28 years before.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] The **1829 State of the Union Address** was delivered by the seventh president of the United States, Andrew Jackson, on December 8, 1829, to the 21st United States Congress.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] This was Jackson's first address to Congress after his election, and it set the tone for his presidency, emphasizing limited government, states’ rights, and the removal of Native Americans from their lands.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] In his address, Jackson expressed satisfaction with the nation's peace and prosperity, noting that the country was “at peace with all mankind” and that domestic affairs were progressing well.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] He acknowledged, however, unresolved disputes with foreign powers, particularly Great Britain, France, and Spain.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] Jackson assured Congress that his administration would work to settle these differences amicably, while maintaining a firm stance on protecting American rights.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] A significant part of the address was dedicated to internal improvements and the national debt.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] Jackson called for a cautious approach to government spending, warning against the dangers of corruption and advocating for reducing the national debt. “It is time to check the tendency to lavish expenditure and make our government as simple and economical as possible,” Jackson urged.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] Jackson also called for a constitutional amendment to reform the presidential election process.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] He suggested eliminating the role of electoral colleges and the House of Representatives in selecting the president, advocating for a direct popular vote to ensure that the will of the people would always prevail in presidential elections.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] The address is also notable for Jackson's call to remove Native American tribes from their ancestral lands in the southern states.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] Jackson argued that their removal to territories west of the Mississippi River was necessary to protect their survival and to avoid conflict with state governments.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] He stated, "Humanity and national honor demand that every effort should be made to avert so great a calamity," referring to the potential extinction of Native tribes.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1829-state-of-the-union-address] Jackson's first State of the Union address marked the beginning of the major policies of his administration, including limited federal intervention, states' rights, and Native American removal, setting the stage for his presidency.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The **1831 National Republican National Convention** was held to determine the presidential ticket of the National Republican Party in the 1832 United States presidential election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The convention was held in Baltimore, Maryland in December 1831.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The party nominated Senator Henry Clay of Kentucky for president and former Representative John Sergeant of Pennsylvania for vice president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The 1831 National Republican National Convention was the first U.S. presidential nominating convention held by a major party, though a third party, the Anti-Masonic Party, had held a presidential nominating convention earlier in 1831.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] 155 delegates from 18 of the 24 states attended the convention.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] Clay was the unanimous choice for president of the party's delegates.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] He was the first sitting member of the United States Senate to be nominated for president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] In the 1832 presidential election, Clay was defeated by President Andrew Jackson of the Democratic Party.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] After the 1832 election, the National Republican Party, the Anti-Masonic Party, and other opponents of Jackson coalesced into the Whig Party.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] Thus, the 1831 convention was the only national convention ever held by the National Republican Party.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] The **1831 State of the Union Address** was delivered by the seventh president of the United States, Andrew Jackson, on December 6, 1831, to the 22nd United States Congress.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] In his third annual message, Jackson highlighted the continued prosperity of the United States, focusing on agricultural success, growth in manufacturing, and advancements in internal improvements.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] He credited these developments to the nation's free institutions and stressed the importance of maintaining the Union.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] Jackson noted that the nation was thriving in trade and commerce, with shipyards full of activity and American vessels trading across the globe.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] He also pointed to the rapid development of railroads and steam power, predicting that these technologies would soon bridge the vast distances within the United States, alleviating concerns about the Union's size threatening its stability.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] In foreign affairs, Jackson celebrated the successful negotiation of a treaty with France, which resolved longstanding claims of indemnity for American citizens whose ships were seized during the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] This treaty, Jackson asserted, would remove a significant source of tension between the two nations.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] He also reported progress on claims with other European nations, including Great Britain and Spain, and emphasized the importance of maintaining friendly and equitable relations with all foreign powers.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] One of the key domestic issues addressed in the speech was the ongoing policy of Indian Removal.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] Jackson noted that treaties with the Chickasaw and Choctaw nations were being executed, leading to their removal west of the Mississippi River.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] He expressed hope that the Cherokee would soon follow suit, allowing for the complete settlement of Mississippi and Alabama by white settlers.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] Jackson framed this policy as both beneficial to the states and to the Native Americans, who he claimed would be better off away from the encroachment of white settlers.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] Jackson also touched on the federal budget, noting the government's strong financial position, with revenue exceeding expectations and allowing for substantial payments toward the national debt.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] He reiterated his support for a reduction in import duties once the debt was fully paid, advocating for a tariff that would protect American industries without placing undue burdens on consumers.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] Finally, Jackson restated his concerns about the Second Bank of the United States, leaving the issue to Congress and the people for further consideration, but reaffirming his opposition to the institution in its current form.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1831-state-of-the-union-address] Andrew Jackson did not attend the November 24, 1831 Philadelphia wedding of Andrew Jackson Jr. and Sarah Yorke because he was consumed with preparing his annual message.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The **1832 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 21 to May 23, 1832, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the first presidential nominating convention ever held by the Democratic Party, incumbent President Andrew Jackson was nominated for a second term, while former Secretary of State Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Anti-Masonic Party and the National Republican Party had held the first presidential nominating conventions in 1831, and Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet" helped organize a Democratic convention in 1832.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] As the party leaders assumed that Jackson would be nominated for president, the primary purpose of the convention was to find a new running mate: Vice President John C.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun had fallen out with Jackson following the Petticoat affair and the Nullification Crisis, and subsequently resigned the office in order to take a Senate seat.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention, which was presided over by Governor Robert Lucas, hosted delegates from every state except Missouri; Jackson won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] With Jackson's strong endorsement, Van Buren easily won the vice presidential nomination on the first ballot, defeating former Representative Philip P.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barbour of Virginia and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Jackson and Van Buren went on to win the 1832 presidential election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the summer of 1822, "Richmond Junto" leader Thomas Ritchie of Virginia began raising the idea of a national convention to resolve the issue of nomination; ultimately, the congressional nominating caucus was appealed to by the devotees of Treasury Secretary William H.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Following that defeat in the election of 1824, early in 1827, Van Buren privately made the argument to Richie for an exclusive national convention of Republicans to ensure Jackson's nomination.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] However, it did not immediately come to fruition while state conventions and legislatures took up Jackson as their presidential candidate for the election of 1828 with Vice President John C.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Such a type of national convention would occur after the election.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun soon became politically estranged from President Jackson, due in part to an 1830 letter written by Crawford stating that Calhoun, as Secretary of War under President James Monroe, pushed for a reprimand of then-General Jackson for his actions in the 1818 invasion of Florida.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Petticoat affair in which Calhoun's wife, Floride, was a central figure further alienated Jackson from the vice president and his supporters.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The final blow to the relationship came in January 1832, when Calhoun, as President of the Senate, sank Van Buren's nomination as Minister to Great Britain by casting a tie-breaking vote in the United States Senate.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Calhoun was replaced as the party's 1832 vice presidential nominee by Van Buren.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Later that year, on December 28, he resigned as vice president, after having been elected to the U.S.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] There he continued to be a proponent of the doctrine of nullification in opposition to Jackson.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The proposal for the convention began with members of Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet", his coterie of informal advisers and confidants.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Major William Berkeley Lewis wrote on May 25, 1831, to Amos Kendall, who was then in New Hampshire.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] He proposed that the New Hampshire legislature call for a national gathering of Republican supporters of the Jackson administration to nominate a candidate for the vice presidency, and asked Kendall to pass the idea to Isaac Hill.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention was called to order by Frederick A.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from all states except Missouri were present.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Governor Robert Lucas of Ohio served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Peter Vivian Daniel, James Fenner, John M.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barclay, and Augustin Smith Clayton were chosen as convention vice presidents.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] John Adams Dix was appointed secretary at the first meeting, with other additional secretaries thereafter.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] A resolution was passed by the convention requiring two-thirds majority support of the delegates for a nomination.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] An address by the Republican delegates of New York gave a history of previous national political activity in the United States.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] They denounced the National Republicans as Federalists under a new designation and they denounced the Nullifiers while they declared that their own party held the middle ground between the positions of the other two.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The address described what they claimed were political similarities between Andrew Jackson and Thomas Jefferson and it defended the policies of Jackson's administration.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] It characterized Van Buren as a strict constructionist and welcomed his nomination.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention concluded by adopting a resolution calling for an address or report from the delegations to their constituents.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Jackson was nominated via a resolution passed by the convention, affirming the nominations which Jackson had previously received from multiple state legislatures.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president on the first ballot after receiving 208 votes of the 283 cast, 19 more than the two-thirds majority required to win.
[src:1832-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Jackson and Martin Van Buren defeated their main competitors, Henry Clay and John Sergeant of the National Republican Party, by a large electoral vote margin in the election of 1832.
